            <div type="translation">
            <p>To Imperator Caesar Domitian Augustus Germanicus, son of the deified Vespasian, high
                    priest, in the fifteenth year of his tribunician power, imperator for the
                    twenty-second time, consul for the seventeenth time, perpetual censor, father of
                    the country, the Flavian Augustan Colony of Puteoli [dedicates this] having been
                    moved closer to his city by the indulgence of the very great and divine leader.
                    (Flower 2001: 629)</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription, dating to 95/96 CE, is engraved on one side of a large marble block
                    from Puteoli, which originally formed the base of a statue dedicated to Domitian
                    by the Colonia Flavia Augusta Puteolana. After Domitian's assassination in 96,
                    the text was completely erased in situ--a rare act of damnatio memoriae, which
                    was usually limited to chiseling out only the emperor's name. Once the
                    inscription had been effaced, the opposite side of the stone was carved to bear
                    a relief with Roman soldiers, likely Praetorian Guardsmen (Romano 2006:
                    262-264). In the inscription, after the full imperial titulature, Domitian is
                    praised for his indulgentia ('benevolence, fatherly kindness'), which represents
                    one of the earliest example of a community employing this term toward its
                    benefactor. In this context, Domitian is celebrated for having moved Puteoli
                    'closer to his city' by connecting the Colonia to Rome through a civil
                    engeneering project, namely the construction of the Via Domitiana, the new
                    coastal road connecting Puteoli with Sinuessa and Rome (Flower 2001). The
                    distinctive usage of the term indulgentia, together with the adjectives
                    'maximus' and 'divinus' jointly applied to the emperor, testifies to the
                    exceptional and intimate bond that exhisted between Puteoli and Domitian, who
                    acts as a benefactor to the community (Puteoli had long been loyal to the
                    Flavians, as its earlier relationship with Vespasian shows). This special bond
                    is later mirrored in the complete and deliberate erasure of the inscription, an
                    act driven by fear and by the need to perform loyalty to Domitian's successors.
                    After its erasure, the block was removed and reused in a Trajanic public
                    monument, likely a monumental altar or an arch featuring reliefs of the
                    Praetorian Guard (at least in part), who now emerge as a new emblem of political
                    loyalty to the the emperor. The Puteoli marble thus stands as an exceptional
                    case of reuse unfolding in three stages: Domitian's exaltation (closely tied to
                    the Via Domitiana, 95/96), erasure and disgrace following his murder (96), and
                    Trajanic reuse of the block (102).</p></div>
            

